content.text:
Now let me analyze the issue more carefully. Looking at the `processNextEvent` method in `EventLoop.common.kt`:

```kotlin
override fun processNextEvent(): Long {
    // unconfined events take priority
    if (processUnconfinedEvent()) return 0
    // queue all delayed tasks that are due to be executed
    val delayed = _delayed.value
    if (delayed != null && !delayed.isEmpty) {
        val now = nanoTime()
        while (true) {
            // make sure that moving from delayed to queue removes from delayed only after it is added to queue
            // to make sure that 'isEmpty' and `nextTime` that check both of them
            // do not transiently report that both delayed and queue are empty during move
            delayed.removeFirstIf {
                if (it.timeToExecute(now)) {
                    enqueueImpl(it)
                } else
                    false
            } ?: break // quit loop when nothing more to remove or enqueueImpl returns false on "isComplete"
        }
    }
    // then process one event from queue
    val task = dequeue()
    if (task != null) {
        platformAutoreleasePool { task.run() }
        return 0
    }
    return nextTime
}
```

The problem is clear: when `yield()` is called, it dispatches the current continuation to the queue via `dispatchYield`. Then when `processNextEvent()` is called, it first moves delayed tasks to the queue, and then dequeues and runs one task. Since the yield continuation was added to the queue first (before the delayed tasks are moved), it gets executed first.

The fix should be to check if there are any delayed tasks that are ready to execute BEFORE adding the yield continuation to the queue. Let me look at how `dispatchYield` is implemented in the EventLoop:

